{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"`=SUM(A1:A10)` returns the correct total for A1..A10.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A pure SUM unit test can miss failures in formula parsing, range resolution, and cell value retrieval wiring. The real failure boundary is evaluator + workbook grid + function dispatch together.","test_description":"Create an in-memory workbook, set A1..A10 to known numeric values, set B1 to `=SUM(A1:A10)`, run evaluation, assert B1 equals expected total; include a mix of ints/floats to catch range coercion issues.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A formula referencing a formula cell (e.g., `B1+1` where `B1=A1*2`) computes correct cascaded value.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This depends on dependency resolution and multi-cell evaluation order across modules. Mocking internals could hide real graph/evaluator wiring bugs.","test_description":"Set A1=5, B1=`=A1*2`, C1=`=B1+1`; evaluate workbook and assert B1=10 and C1=11.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.87,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Circular references (A1->B1, B1->A1) return a circular dependency error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Cycle detection is a property of the dependency graph plus evaluator traversal, not one isolated function. Unit tests can miss real recursion/wiring failure modes.","test_description":"Set A1=`=B1+1` and B1=`=A1+1`, evaluate, assert a typed circular-reference error is returned and evaluation terminates without hang.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"`VLOOKUP` exact match returns correct value; missing key returns error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures often come from interaction of table-range lookup, type comparison, and function registry/parsing, which mocks can hide.","test_description":"Populate a lookup table range, evaluate one formula with existing key and one with missing key, assert correct returned value and expected not-found error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Nested `IF` conditions evaluate correctly (`high`/`medium`/`low`).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Nested condition correctness depends on parser AST shape plus evaluator branching semantics across modules.","test_description":"Use three A1 values (e.g., 25, 15, 5) against `=IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")`; assert outputs are `high`, `medium`, `low` respectively.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"`CONCATENATE` joins values with separator and skips empty cells.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Skipping empty referenced cells depends on reference resolution and function argument handling together; a function-only mock can miss sheet-value semantics.","test_description":"Set cells with text and empties, evaluate a CONCATENATE formula with separators, assert output omits separators for skipped empty cells per spec.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Cross-sheet reference (e.g., `=Sheet2!A1+1`) resolves when target sheet exists.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Needs workbook multi-sheet namespace resolution plus evaluator wiring. Unit tests of arithmetic alone would miss sheet reference binding errors.","test_description":"Create Sheet1 and Sheet2, set Sheet2!A1=41, set Sheet1!B1=`=Sheet2!A1+1`, evaluate and assert Sheet1!B1=42.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.89,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Changing a referenced cell triggers dependent recalculation in correct topological order.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is fundamentally dependency graph invalidation + scheduler ordering + evaluator interaction. Mocking any layer may hide stale-value/order bugs.","test_description":"Build chain/diamond dependencies (e.g., A1->B1,C1->D1), evaluate once, mutate A1, recalc, assert all affected cells updated to expected values with no stale intermediates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"Undo after formula edit restores prior formula text and dependent computed values.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Requires editor state/history + recalculation engine integration. Unit-testing undo stack alone can miss recomputation rollback failures.","test_description":"Set up formula with dependents, evaluate, edit formula to new expression and recalc, perform undo, assert original formula text restored and dependent cells return to pre-edit values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Save/load workbook in custom binary format preserves formulas, values, and floating-point precision.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is serializer/deserializer + workbook model + filesystem I/O path. Pure mocks can hide binary encoding/decoding regressions.","test_description":"Cr